suffix:
By adding a class to either the first <code>tr</code> or the subsequent <code>tr</code>s. There is no crossbrowser way of selecting the rows you want with CSS alone.
However, if you don't care about Internet Explorer 6, 7 or 8:
<code>tr:not(:first-child) {
    color: red;
}
</code>
Though the question has a decent answer already, I just want to stress that the <code>:first-child</code> tag goes on the item type that represents the children.
For example, in the code:
<code>&lt;div id"someDiv"&gt;
     &lt;input id="someInput1" /&gt; 
     &lt;input id="someInput2" /&gt;
     &lt;input id="someInput2" /&gt;
&lt;/div
</code>
If you want to affect only the second two elements with a margin, but not the first, you would do:
<code>#someDiv &gt; input {
     margin-top: 20px;
}
#someDiv &gt; input:first-child{
     margin-top: 0px;
}
</code>
that is, since the <code>input</code>s are the children, you would place <code>first-child</code> on the input portion of the selector.
ideal solution but not supported in IE
<code>tr:not(:first-child) {css}
</code>
second solution would be to style all tr's and then override with css for first-child:
<code>tr {css}
tr:first-child {override css above}
</code>
I'm surprised nobody mentioned the use of sibling combinators, which are supported by IE7 and later:
<code>tr + tr /* CSS2, adjacent sibling */
tr ~ tr /* CSS3, general sibling */
</code>
They both function in exactly the same way (in the context of HTML tables anyway) as:
<code>tr:not(:first-child)
</code>
Another option:
<code>tr:nth-child(n + 2) {
    /* properties */
}
</code>

